          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>a00f********242b</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********673G</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-johnw-src-dot-emacs-lisp-org-drafts/3bdcad0d-ed94-4223-9b6f-60d0eda3160f/tasks/a00fdfe9668eb242b.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Research Elisp lint/format tools\" completed</summary>\n<result>Good, I now have a comprehensive picture. Let me compile the findings.\n\n---\n\nHere is a thorough summary of the current landscape for Elisp linting and formatting in CI/batch mode.\n\n## 1. Emacs Lisp Linting Tools for Batch Mode / CI\n\nThere are several distinct tools, each catching a different category of problems. Best practice is to layer them together.\n\n### A. byte-compile (built-in)\n\nThe single most important check. Catches undefined functions, unused variables, wrong argument counts, deprecated API usage, and more.\n\n```bash\nemacs --batch -L . -f batch-byte-compile org-drafts.el\n```\n\nTo make warnings into hard errors (fail CI on any warning):\n\n```bash\nemacs --batch -L . \\\n  --eval \"(setq byte-compile-error-on-warn t)\" \\\n  -f batch-byte-compile org-drafts.el\n```\n\n### B. checkdoc (built-in)\n\nValidates docstrings against GNU Emacs documentation conventions: first-line formatting, argument references in caps, sentence-ending periods, and so on.\n\nBatch invocation is somewhat awkward because `checkdoc` was designed interactively, but it works:\n\n```bash\nemacs --batch \\\n  --eval \"(require 'checkdoc)\" \\\n  --eval \"(with-current-buffer (find-file-noselect \\\"org-drafts.el\\\")\n            (let ((checkdoc-diagnostic-buffer \\\"*warn*\\\"))\n              (checkdoc-current-buffer t)))\"\n```\n\nIf you use **Eask**, this becomes simply:\n\n```bash\neask lint checkdoc\n```\n\n### C. package-lint (MELPA package)\n\nChecks Elisp package metadata and conventions: proper header format, dependency declarations, namespace prefix consistency, GPL-compatible license headers, and missing `;;;###autoload` cookies. This is what MELPA checks before accepting packages.\n\nBatch invocation:\n\n```bash\nemacs --batch \\\n  --eval \"(require 'package)\" \\\n  --eval \"(push '(\\\"melpa\\\" . \\\"https://melpa.org/packages/\\\") package-archives)\" \\\n  --eval \"(package-initialize)\" \\\n  --eval \"(package-refresh-contents)\" \\\n  --eval \"(unless (package-installed-p 'package-lint) (package-install 'package-lint))\" \\\n  --eval \"(require 'package-lint)\" \\\n  -f package-lint-batch-and-exit org-drafts.el\n```\n\nThe key function is `package-lint-batch-and-exit`, which accepts filenames as command-line arguments and exits non-zero on errors.\n\nWith Eask:\n\n```bash\neask lint package\n```\n\n### D. check-declare (built-in)\n\nValidates that `(declare-function ...)` forms match the actual function signatures in the declared files. This catches cases where you declared a function with the wrong argument list or from the wrong file.\n\n```bash\nemacs --batch \\\n  --eval \"(require 'check-declare)\" \\\n  --eval \"(check-declare-directory \\\"/path/to/source/\\\")\"\n```\n\nWith Eask:\n\n```bash\neask lint declare\n```\n\n### E. relint (MELPA package, by mattiase)\n\nA specialized linter for regular expressions in Elisp code. It catches invalid regexp syntax, redundant groups, suspicious character classes, and other regexp-specific bugs. This is genuinely useful -- regexp bugs are notoriously hard to spot by eye.\n\nBatch invocation:\n\n```bash\nemacs --batch -l relint -f relint-batch org-drafts.el\n```\n\nOr for a whole directory:\n\n```bash\nemacs --batch -l relint -f relint-directory .\n```\n\nWith Eask:\n\n```bash\neask lint regexps\n```\n\n### F. elisp-lint (archived -- gonewest818/elisp-lint)\n\nThis was a popular meta-linter that combined byte-compile, checkdoc, package-lint, and indent checks into one tool. However, it was **archived and removed from MELPA around 2022**. It is no longer maintained. Its functionality is now better covered by running the individual tools above or by using Eask.\n\n### G. Eask as a Unified Runner\n\nIf you adopt Eask for your project, it wraps all of the above into clean subcommands:\n\n| Command | What it runs |\n|---|---|\n| `eask lint checkdoc` | checkdoc |\n| `eask lint package` | package-lint |\n| `eask lint declare` | check-declare |\n| `eask lint regexps` | relint |\n| `eask lint indent` | indentation consistency check |\n| `eask compile` | byte-compile (with warnings) |\n\nThis is the most convenient approach for CI if you are willing to adopt Eask as your build tool.\n\n### H. makem.sh (alphapapa/makem.sh)\n\nA standalone shell script by alphapapa (Adam Porter) that provides a CI-friendly wrapper around Emacs batch operations: linting, byte-compilation, and test running (ERT, Buttercup). It does not require Eask or Cask -- it bootstraps a sandboxed Emacs environment itself. Worth considering if you want something lightweight with no build-tool dependency.\n\n### Best Practice: Layer These Checks\n\nA robust CI pipeline should run, in this order:\n\n1. **byte-compile** with `byte-compile-error-on-warn` -- catches the most bugs\n2. **package-lint** -- catches packaging and convention issues\n3. **checkdoc** -- catches documentation problems\n4. **check-declare** -- catches stale or incorrect declare-function forms\n5. **relint** -- catches regexp errors (if your package uses regexps)\n\n---\n\n## 2. Emacs Lisp Code Formatting in Batch Mode\n\n### A. elisp-autofmt (ideasman42/elisp-autofmt)\n\nThis is the closest thing to `gofmt` or `black` for Elisp. It is available on MELPA, actively maintained by Campbell Barton (ideasman42, also a Blender core developer), and produces idiomatic, consistent Elisp formatting.\n\n**Batch invocation:**\n\n```bash\nemacs --batch \\\n  --load /path/to/elisp-autofmt.el \\\n  org-drafts.el \\\n  -f elisp-autofmt-batch\n```\n\nThe function `elisp-autofmt-batch` reads filenames from the command-line arguments and formats them in place. This makes it suitable for pre-commit hooks.\n\n**Important caveat:** elisp-autofmt has its own formatting opinions. It will reformat your code to match its style, which may not match your current style exactly. Test it on your codebase first before adopting it for CI enforcement.\n\n### B. Emacs built-in indent-region (no extra packages)\n\nIf you just want to enforce standard Emacs Lisp indentation (without any other formatting changes like line breaking or alignment), you can use Emacs's own indentation engine in batch mode:\n\n```bash\nemacs --batch \\\n  --eval \"(progn\n            (find-file \\\"org-drafts.el\\\")\n            (emacs-lisp-mode)\n            (indent-region (point-min) (point-max))\n            (save-buffer))\"\n```\n\nThis applies the standard `emacs-lisp-mode` indentation rules. It only fixes indentation depth -- it will not reflow lines, add/remove blank lines, or change anything else.\n\n**For a check-only mode** (detect if indentation differs, without modifying the file):\n\n```bash\nemacs --batch \\\n  --eval \"(progn\n            (find-file \\\"org-drafts.el\\\")\n            (emacs-lisp-mode)\n            (let ((original (buffer-string)))\n              (indent-region (point-min) (point-max))\n              (unless (string= original (buffer-string))\n                (message \\\"Indentation differs\\\")\n                (kill-emacs 1))))\"\n```\n\nThis is what `eask lint indent` does under the hood.\n\n### C. elisp-format (Xah Lee)\n\nAn older tool. Less actively maintained than elisp-autofmt. Generally not recommended for new adoption.\n\n### Practical Recommendation\n\nFor formatting, the two realistic options are:\n\n- **elisp-autofmt** if you want a full opinionated formatter (analogous to `black` for Python or `gofmt` for Go)\n- **indent-region in batch mode** if you only want to enforce consistent indentation without changing anything else\n\nFor a project like org-drafts where you are the sole author and the code is already well-formatted, the `indent-region` check-only approach (or `eask lint indent`) is likely the better fit -- it catches accidental indentation mistakes without imposing a different style.\n\n---\n\n## Summary for a Minimal CI Setup (no Eask)\n\nA pre-commit hook or GitHub Actions step for org-drafts could look like this:\n\n```bash\n#!/bin/bash\nset -e\n\nFILE=\"org-drafts.el\"\n\n# 1. Byte-compile with warnings as errors\nemacs --batch -L . \\\n  --eval \"(setq byte-compile-error-on-warn t)\" \\\n  -f batch-byte-compile \"$FILE\"\n\n# 2. Check indentation consistency\nemacs --batch \\\n  --eval \"(progn\n            (find-file \\\"$FILE\\\")\n            (emacs-lisp-mode)\n            (let ((original (buffer-string)))\n              (indent-region (point-min) (point-max))\n              (unless (string= original (buffer-string))\n                (message \\\"Indentation is inconsistent\\\")\n                (kill-emacs 1))))\"\n\necho \"All checks passed.\"\n```\n\nAdd `package-lint`, `checkdoc`, and `relint` checks as your needs grow.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>20962</total_tokens><tool_uses>20</tool_uses><duration_ms>193960</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>",
